article.headline: California 85, Arizona State 83
article.story: BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- California lost three of its first five Pac-10 games this season, but with the second half of the conference schedule under way, the Golden Bears are one of the hottest teams in the league. Behind a season-high 24 points from Marquise Kately and 20 from Richard Midgley, all in the second half, California beat Arizona State 85-83 Saturday, the Bears' third straight victory and fifth in their last six games. Combined with No. 12 Arizona's loss to Stanford earlier in the day, the victory moved California (11-9, 7-4) into sole possession of second place in the Pac-10. "I think we're in the place we want to be," said Leon Powe, who had 13 points and 11 rebounds for the Bears. "From where we came from and where we're at, we came a long way. We're in second, we're doing good, we've won three in a row. That's where we want to be." Amit Tamir also scored 13 for the Bears. Ike Diogu scored a game-high 33 points for Arizona State (8-12, 2-9), which missed a chance to win when Kevin Kruger's rushed 3-point attempt fell short at the buzzer. Midgley hit two free throws to give the Bears an 85-78 lead with 1:34 to play, but Arizona State made it close with five quick points. Wilfried Fameni hit a 3-pointer and then Jason Braxton had a steal and a lay-up to make it 85-83 with 53 seconds remaining. The Sun Devils got the ball back on a turnover, but could not get a clear shot and had to settle for Kruger's hurried 3-point attempt. "I did not see contact, but you're not going to get a call like that late in the game," said Sun Devils coach Rob Evans, whose team lost despite a season-high 12 3-pointers. "I saw a lot of contact all game." Most of the whistles went against Arizona State. California hit 26 of a season-high 42 free throws, the most attempts from the line by a California team since Dec. 11, 2000, when they put up 45 against Albany. Kately was 10-of-17 from the line. California led for most of the first half, but scored only two baskets over the final 9:20 and trailed 42-40 at the break. Stevie Moore's 16-foot jumper brought Arizona State within 65-63 with 8:34 remaining in the game, but Powe and Midgley combined for 18 of California's final 20 points to help seal the victory. "I liked that we were able to turn it up a little bit in the second half," said California coach Ben Braun. "There were some lulls. We're having fewer of those now, but it's still a lesson for us. We have to stay on top the whole way." Jamal Hill scored 17 points and Kruger added 12 for Arizona State. California scored the first six points of the game and led 24-14 following two straight 3-pointers by Dominic McGuire. But then the Bears turned cold, allowing Arizona State to come back. The Sun Devils took their first lead, 28-27, on a jumper by Diogu. Back-to-back 3-pointers by Diogu and Moore later built the Arizona State lead to 37-31 before California sank seven free throws over the final three minutes to help close the Sun Devil lead to 42-40 at halftime.
